Feature: BrowserCloud browser automation infrastructure
  BrowserCloud differentiates by packaging cloud browsers, proxies, CAPTCHA solving, and recording behind transparent credit plans.

  Scenario: Start a cloud browser for an AI app
    Given a developer has a BrowserCloud account and API key
    When they launch a headed or headless browser through a supported framework
    Then the platform provides browser automation capacity without local Chrome management
    And the run can use screenshots, PDFs, live monitoring, or session recording

  Scenario: Scale a scraping workload
    Given a workload needs many pages and concurrent sessions
    When the buyer selects a plan with enough monthly credits and browser concurrency
    Then the workload can consume browser hours, HTTP page scrapes, screenshots, PDFs, and proxy traffic from the plan
    And enterprise buyers can negotiate custom concurrency and RPM limits

  Scenario: Reach sites that block simple automation
    Given a target site requires stealth, proxies, or CAPTCHA handling
    When the workflow enables BrowserCloud's anti-detection and proxy features
    Then the browser run attempts to complete the workflow with fewer manual interventions

  # Good: concrete pricing and concurrency make capacity planning easier.
  # Bad: the product exposes less run semantics and evidence UX than an agent-first browser workspace.
